raw_events.text:
**alienalien**

Ellie always felt invisible, blending into the patchy fields outside her small town. One dusky evening, a shimmering light split the sky and crashed into the old Miller farm. Curiosity burning brighter than fear, Ellie crept out to investigate, and there—amid twisted metal and flashing buttons—she met them.

Zorp was tall and green, his eight eyes flickering with worry. Blip was round, blue, and bounced nervously whenever Ellie spoke. Their spaceship hummed and sputtered, leaking what smelled suspiciously like caramel syrup. The aliens wobbled, panicked, exchanging warbly beeps until Ellie offered them her hand.

“Don’t worry. I can help,” she said, smiling.

The aliens’ translation bubble whirred. “Will you help us not be caught by your Terran enforcers?” Zorp asked, blinking three eyes at a time.

Ellie nodded. She knew all about being scared. Together, they snuck under fences and dodged searchlights, laughing when Blip’s hiccup sent them tumbling into haybales. Ellie smuggled car batteries and glitter glue from her garage, while Zorp read the manual (upside-down) and Blip drew blueprints with chocolate syrup.

But the government agents soon sniffed out strange readings from Miller’s farm. Ellie and her friends hid in the cornfield, Zorp quivering. “We will be specimens!”

“No one’s making you a specimen,” Ellie promised, clutching their hands.

Together, they worked through the night, sharing stories—about Zorp’s home, where everyone loved to untangle space-vines, and about Blip, whose people sang storms into rainbows. Ellie told them about being alone at school, and her longing for a true friend. The stars blinked in approval.

When the agents finally burst into the barn, the trio activated their hastily repaired ship. Blip pressed the launch button with a giggle. The spaceship, patched with glittering tape and humming on car battery fumes, lifted Ellie into the sky with them for a final, looping goodbye.

“You’re not alone, Ellie,” Zorp promised. “On our world, we have a word—‘Grineel’—for friends that feel like home.”

They beamed her back, heart full and cheeks damp. As the ship shot beyond the clouds, Ellie waved, knowing her world had grown bigger—and that, sometimes, the best friends come from far away.

After all, being different had brought them together, and now she’d never feel invisible again.
